{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> σκῆπτρον</b>, τό: <br /> <i>Doric dialect</i> <b>σκᾶπτον</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"(5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 7.28, “P.” 1.6, etc.)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>], later <b>σκᾶπτρον</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"(“Anthologia Graeca” 7.428 (1st c.BC: Meleager Epigrammaticus)), but σκῆπτρον\">Refs 1st c.BC+</a>] in Lyric poetry passages of Trag., as [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 140 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: (σκήπτω):— <b>staff</b> or <b>stick</b>, used by the lame or aged, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 18.416, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 13.437, 14.31, 17.199, 18.103; ἰσχὺν.. νέμοντες ἐπὶ σκήπτροις 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 75 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; σκήπτρῳ προδεικνύς, of a blind man feeling his way, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 456; πρεσβῦται.. σκήπτροισιν ἄκασκα προβῶντες 5th c.BC: Cratinus Comicus 126: _metaphorically_ of the daughters of Oedipus, ὦ σκῆπτρα φωτός\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] his <b>staffs</b> or <b>supports</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 1109, compare 848:\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] —the Prose word is βακτηρία. <br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <b>staff</b> or <b>baton</b>, especially as the badge of command, <b>sceptre</b>: in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] borne by kings and chiefs, and transmitted from father to son (whence [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.101 ff. is called ἡ τοῦ σκήπτρου παράδοσις, 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 1.9), 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 9.156, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 11.569 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: also borne by heralds, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 7.277, +others\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; by speakers, who on rising to speak received it from the herald, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1.234, 18.505, 23.568, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 2.37 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; by priests and soothsayers, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.15, 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 1265 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; later by minstrels, first in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Theogonia” 30; σ. χρύσεον 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.15, 2.268, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 11.91, 569 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; wrought by Hephaestus, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.101; χρυσείοις ἥλοισι πεπαρμένον 1.245. In oaths or protests it was held up, the gods being called to witness, [prev. work] 234, 7.412, 10.321, 328 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ὁ δ᾽ ὅρκος ἦν τοῦ σ. ἐπανάτασις [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Politica” 1285b12 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; used as a <b>stick</b> or <b>cudgel</b> to punish the refractory, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.199, 265, 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 7.28, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 811. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> as a symbol of <b>royalty, kingly power</b>, etc., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 6.159, 9.38; τοι Ζεὺς ἐγγυάλιξε σκῆπτρόν τ᾽ ἠδὲ θέμιστας [prev. work] 99, compare 156, 298, 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 172 (_anapaest meter_)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; τὸ θεῖον Διὸς σ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 140 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: frequently in <i>plural</i> in this sense, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 7.52 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τύραννα σ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 761, compare “Eu.” 626; ὃς.. σκῆπτρα καὶ θρόνους ἔχει 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 425, compare 449, etc.; σκῆπτρα χώρας 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hercules Furens” 1167. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> = Hebrew “Shevet”, of the tribes (φυλαί) of Israel, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" LXX.1Ki.11.13, +others(but in LXX.1Ki.10.20f, φυλή is a sub-division of σκῆπτρον). \">LXX</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__IV</b></Level2> ={λυχνὶς στεφανωματική}, Ps.[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.AD: Dioscorides (Dioscurides) Medicus 3.100. \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]","strongNumber":"G9104","accentedUnicode":"σκῆπτρον","shortDef":"a chiefdom; staff","mediumDef":"a chiefdom; staff","stepGloss":"a chiefdom","stepTransliteration":"skēptron","count":0,"_step_Type":"word"}]}